Once running, visit http://localhost:3000/api-docs for interactive API documentation.

Key Endpoints
Inventory Management

GET    /inventory/stock/:productId     Get current stock level
POST   /inventory/stock                Update stock level
POST   /inventory/reserve              Reserve stock for order
DELETE /inventory/reserve/:id          Cancel reservation
GET    /inventory/items                List inventory items

Product Management

GET    /products                      List all products
POST   /products                      Create new product
GET    /products/:id                  Get product details
PUT    /products/:id                  Update product
DELETE /products/:id                  Delete product

Warehouse Management

GET    /warehouses                    List warehouses
POST   /warehouses                    Create warehouse
GET    /warehouses/:id/stock          Get warehouse stock levels

Authentication
The API supports two authentication methods:

JWT Tokens - For user authentication:

Authorization: Bearer <jwt-token>

API Keys - For service-to-service communication:

X-API-Key: <api-key>

Testing

# Unit tests
npm test

# E2E tests
npm run test:e2e

# Test coverage
npm run test:cov

Deployment

Kubernetes
# Apply Kubernetes manifests
kubectl apply -f k8s/namespace.yaml
kubectl apply -f k8s/configmap.yaml
kubectl apply -f k8s/secrets.yaml
kubectl apply -f k8s/deployment.yaml
kubectl apply -f k8s/service.yaml
kubectl apply -f k8s/ingress.yaml


AWS ECS

# Build and push image
docker build -t your-registry/inventory-api:latest .
docker push your-registry/inventory-api:latest

# Deploy with ECS CLI
ecs-cli compose --project-name inventory-api up
